{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5c6c669-1c12-4965-8739-5da316e76601","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead. It's more precise — it scopes the assertion to the exact call:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why?** `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line in the test throws, which can mask bugs. `Assert.ThrowsException` targets the specific call and also lets you inspect the exception:\n\n```csharp\nvar ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n    () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\nAssert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ae8d02d3-475f-46e6-a0e5-a080c6bd8a1b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question - no need to explore the codebase.","outputTokens":276,"requestId":"5C24:C4D03:20B798:28FBF3:69F5520D"},"id":"6c8e55e8-7dd1-4421-b97c-cbfea9f1f721","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:23:31.415Z","parentId":"75614f7e-692b-4400-9311-6b4d04ff0513"}
